##With 50 new cases of pneumonia confirmed, is "no mask" slow in Singapore?

DBS, Singapore's largest commercial bank, confirmed Monday that a staff member at the bank was infected with COVID-19. As of noon, Singapore confirmed 50 cases of new coronavirus infection, in addition to the "Diamond Princess" cruise ship disease affected Japan, is the largest number of cases outside China.

According to a report in Lianhe Zaobao on the 12th, dbs announced in the afternoon that a staff member had been infected with the new coronavirus. The staff member was tested the day before and was diagnosed that morning.

DBS said it had evacuated the affected floors of its Marina Bay Financial Centre building by 12:00 that day, had disinfected its offices and was tracing contacts, the rest of the bank's staff will work from home.

It is understood that the Marina Bay Financial Centre has a total of three office buildings, mainly occupied by financial institutions, law firms, business information technology companies, multinational mining and food trading companies, standard Chartered, Baker & McKenzie, etc. . Among them, DBS Bank headquarters is located in the three altogether 46 floors.

According to Reuters 12 reports, DBS bank evacuation of the affected floors of three 43. The bank's Singapore head, Shee Tse Koon, told staff in an internal memo that 300 people on the floor needed to be evacuated.

A singapore-based financial industry source told Marina Bay Financial Centre on the 12th that all floors except the 43rd floor of the three towers are still in normal operation. He said the centre was just 11 minutes away from Grand Hyatt Hong Kong, where cases had been confirmed, and that in addition to dbs, a number of financial institutions in the vicinity had now also reported suspected cases and were being screened.

###Unknown source and community infection

The Singapore government has raised the alert level from yellow to orange (the highest being red) following a case of infection from an unknown source on February 7, confirming signs of community infection.

Singapore has confirmed 50 new cases of pneumonia as of 12 noon, the Ministry of Health reported. Among them, 22 cases were imported from abroad, 28 cases were infected locally, and 8 cases were infected from unknown sources. Among them, 8 cases were serious, 27 cases were stable and 15 cases were cured.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: Ministry of Health

Until 7 days ago, most of the local cases in Singapore were related to the Drug Company Wing Tai Fung and the Grand Hyatt Hong Kong that held the industry meeting. On the 4th, two employees of Yongtaifeng, which had received a Chinese tour group, were diagnosed. The domestic worker of one of the employees and a tour guide who had gone to the shop were also diagnosed on the 5th, the above staff and three relatives of the tour guide have been re-confirmed.

As of noon on the 12th, the number of confirmed cases related to wing Tai Hang had reached 9. There were also three confirmed cases related to Grand Hyatt Hong Kong, diagnosed on June 6 and August 8, respectively. Malaysia and South Korea have previously confirmed one case in connection with two meetings held at the hotel.

But from the 7th, Singapore began to see more cases with no Chinese travel history and unknown sources of infection, the cases have been reported in the Christian Life Church, the Victoria Junior College, the Resorts World Sentosa, six of them recently traveled to Malaysia, and two are Bangladeshi.

The Ministry of Health is currently tracking close contacts of confirmed patients through telephone interviews, Verification and verification of data, and is expanding the scope of testing to provide faster diagnostic tests for suspected cases. As of the 12th, 961 people had been placed under quarantine, 638 tested negative and 125 are being tested.

Starting this week, some offices in Singapore's financial district have started monitoring employees'body temperatures and posting reminders, and some companies, including DBS, have switched from offline meetings to teleconferences.

###"false security. "

Despite the apparent order of things, Singapore's response to the outbreak looks "ambitious" to the outside world. Not only in the evening of 7 held the "people of good faith Lantern Festival, " the Singapore Air Show also opened on the 11th as usual.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
United Evening News on the 6th, "people believe in the Lantern Festival, " the report

However, affected by the epidemic, the number of people attending the Lantern Festival compared with the previous year's million people more than cut in half. More than 70 international exhibitors, including Lockheed Martin, Bombardier and de Havilland, have also dropped out of the show.

For now, the Ministry of Health is responding to the outbreak with similar advice from the World Health Organization, such as don't eat undercooked meat, avoid crowded places, maintain good personal hygiene and so on. For schools and other places, but also issued a stop large-scale activities, staff rest and other corresponding measures.

However, as the number of confirmed cases increases in Singapore, recommendations on the use of face masks are becoming controversial. The country's Health Ministry said only that if you have symptoms such as a cough or a runny nose, be sure to wear a mask, respiratory disease said.

In response, Ministry of Health Gan Kim Yong said on the 7th, contact, droplet infection is the new coronavirus the most important transmission route, there is no evidence that the virus is transmitted through the air, despite signs of local community infection, healthy people still don't need to wear masks, and frequent hand washing is the best defense. "healthy people wearing masks tend to give us a false sense of security, " he said

Xiao A, who studied abroad at Nanyang Technological University, told interface news that she has observed that there are still relatively few people wearing masks at school, and that the majority of students are Chinese, and classes with fewer than 50 students are still in session.

She said that some face masks will be issued by colleges in a position to do so, but measures to prevent and control the epidemic on campus mainly include taking body temperature in the morning and afternoon, as well as stepping up disinfection work in dormitories and other places, targeting teachers and students returning from key areas, separate dormitories have also been set up.

In her view, Singapore's reaction was indeed something of a surprise. Originally thought to have "SARS" lesson in front, Singapore this time will be very strict, but now seems to "slow down" , may be to not let people panic.

In Singapore's alert level, orange indicates that the disease is serious, easily transmissible from person to person, but has not yet spread widely in Singapore, the epidemic is under control. Under the orange alert, moderate measures such as isolation, thermometry, and restricted hospital access are required. Singapore also issued an orange alert during the SARS epidemic in 2003, when 238 cases of infection and 33 deaths occurred.

###"Not as much as the front. "

According to the epidemic figures released at 22:00 on the 12th, the current fatality rate of NCP is about 0.43% in the rest of China outside Hubei and about 3.2% in Hubei. The average mortality rate for SARS was about 9.6 per cent.

Singapore's Prime Minister, Lee Hsien Loong, said on Monday that if the epidemic spread uncontrollably, the death rate could be similar to the 0.01 percent death rate from the flu, and the strategy might change.

But the government has not been slow to respond. Xiao a said the government has been tracking the activities of the appropriate people. She learned that the Ministry of Manpower was also contacting foreign workers with work permits who were working in Singapore through text messages, phone calls and even raids to ask for their location.

Singapore's "orange alert" outbreak response system (DORSCON) is also the country in the "SARS" after the preparation of an epidemic prevention plan.

The system not only explains in detail the preventive measures under relevant circumstances, cross-departmental coordination of the government, border control, public communication, emergency materials procurement and other response measures, there are also guidelines for quarantine, treatment, visits and even disposal of bodies in the event of an outbreak.

Xiao B, who works in the education industry in Singapore, told interface news that departments and agencies still hold tight when it comes to measuring body temperature. At her workplace, she will be asked to go home if her body temperature exceeds 37.5 degrees, all visitors are also required to have their temperature taken before entering the house.

Each family living in Singapore can also get four ordinary masks on the strength of their identity documents, but only once, she said. Still, most of those who questioned the government's move were Chinese people who studied or worked in Singapore, and the locals she knew were relatively cool, even though supermarkets now carry fewer items than they used to, but not all of it.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Singapore on the 7th Upgrade "orange alert" , some supermarkets have appeared "panic buying wave. Source: Twitter

Lee Hsien Loong also stressed in his speech on the 8th that Singapore has further upgraded the level and measures of epidemic prevention and control, including reducing the flow of people in schools and reducing the possibility of cross infection in hospitals, take a more cautious approach to large public gatherings, etc. .

He said the government was thinking ahead and preparing in advance. If the fatality rate rises, the government will also change measures to encourage people with mild illnesses to see a family GP and rest at home, thus leaving strained hospital resources for those who are less resistant to the virus.

As for "should I wear a mask? " His wife, Ho Ching, had answered the previous day. Medical Surgical Masks and materials are in short supply around the world because more than 50 percent of the world's surgical masks were made in China before the outbreak, she wrote on social media.

Now that Vietnam, Thailand and other places have banned or restricted exports, Ho Ching said, Singapore has some stockpiles but will run out if the outbreak continues for some time. "As a precaution, we should give priority to the medical staff who will be at the forefront of the epidemic. "

Ministry of Health Gan Kim Yong, the head of the Department of Health, said Thursday that a million masks would be distributed to private clinics.

Of course, in the opinion of some doctors, people in a position to do so should take precautions in their daily lives. On Monday, four doctors from three clinics in Singapore and one in Australia issued an open letter reminding people to wear masks when they go out.

One of The doctors, Kelyne Tomas, told The Online Citizen in Singapore that as of noon, seven of The 47 confirmed cases were critically ill and were cause for alarm, "We should pay more attention when the critical illness rate is not above 0.2. "

What are you gonNA do without a mask? "Use your head, " the letter said. "for example, someone who buys a washable mask, sews it up, adds a bit of proper paper, or wraps a scarf around their face is better than no mask at all. "
